California nebula distance 1,000 light years.

insta_description:

Un silenzio cos√¨ profondo che ti sorprenderai che qualsiasi piccolo movimento, persino il luccichio delle stelle, non echeggi intorno a te.
Il tempo trascorso in quel posto riesce a donare un senso di concentrazione, felicit√† e calma che difficilmente riuscirai a provare nella vita. 
√à come premere il pulsante Reset nella tua mente che ti permetter√† di lasciare il deserto con occhi pi√π chiari e gentili con cui guardare il mondo e sentendo l‚Äôenergia pulsare nelle vene. 
√à un posto fatto di magia, di questo ne sono certa, hai la sensazione che il tempo si fermi. Bastano due giorni a farti chiedere se siano passati mesi, anni o solo pochi attimi. E arrampicatevi, arrampicatevi su qualsiasi roccia possibile. 
Molte sembrano imponenti, ma basta avvicinarsi per scoprire che Madre Natura ha letteralmente lasciato le pietre miliari per raggiungere la cima. Saltellare tra una roccia e l‚Äôaltra vi far√† sentire proprio come delle formiche su un marciapiede. 
Anche 24 ore sono sufficienti per tornare in contatto con s√© stessi. C‚Äô√® senza dubbio qualcosa in quelle stelle brillanti e nelle ore trascorse a vagare sotto il sole vibrante, qualcosa che mi fa sempre voler rimanere un po‚Äô di pi√π in quella magia.

insta_description:
Good Tuesday morning everyone.. As I was strolling down the little , red brick sidewalks this early Tuesday morning, I wanted you guys to enjoy what I was seeing.  Being out in nature, hearing the birds sing sweetly, just brings such a peace and calm to my soul. Listening to the water, trickling over the small pebbles in the creek is so soothing. I am reminded of a Bible verse where Jesus told the disciples to "come unto me ,all ye that labor and I will give you rest . "There's rest and peace in Jesus my friends, even in the midst of our crisis. Just cast all our worries and cares on Him , and trust Him to work all things out for our good.  Find your hope and peace in Jesus today who has promised never to leave us or forsake us. A friend until the end. My prayers today are for our great leaders and the safety and health of all nations. Remember there's always someone else who has more problems than we do and to be thankful for all our blessings.

Here, on a coveted corner lot set high above the city and the bay, this imposing 11,600¬± sq.ft. mansion is the foremost offering on the market in San Francisco, presenting a rare opportunity to own a custom-built residence in a world-class location with world-class views. Impressively engineered of concrete and steel and completed circa 2004, it displays quality construction, craftsmanship and refinement.

The eminently comfortable home has six bedrooms‚Äîfive en suite‚Äîseven full baths, and two half baths. Floors are clad in walnut, raw limestone and marble. High-ceilinged public spaces are airy, open, and ideal for entertaining on any scale. The centerpiece of the home is a spectacular serpentine staircase with ornate railings crafted by Italian artisans. The property features interior design by both Ken Fulk and Eric Cohler, elevator access to four levels, a secondary back staircase, smart home technology, radiant heating, two working fireplaces, hand-plastered walls, mahogany doors and windows, a four-car garage with an EV charging station, and abundant storage.

A formal entry facing Broadway begins with a grand portrait hall with 20-foot ceilings, marble floors, and a dramatic double staircase. An extensive wine cellar with tasting area is also located on this level. The second level is comprised of a study and two bedrooms, including a two-room guest suite. On the third level is a vibrant, open library with mahogany-paneled walls, coffered ceilings, built-in bookcases, a bay window with a lovely view, and a decorative fireplace with a custom glass mosaic. The handsome pub and billiards room has an antique bar reclaimed from a British tavern. Completing this level are an elegant guest suite with quilted leather walls, a private fitness room.

.
Let‚Äôs take care of each other while we‚Äôre here. Practice social distancing, work from home if possible, and remember that you could be contagious even if you have no symptoms.
.

.
I‚Äôve been so inspired by the videos of communal singing in Italy, and the way many individuals are offering to care for the more vulnerable. I know we‚Äôll see even more of this in the future.
.

"Many farmers rely on groundwater, especially in dry years. Some Southern California cities also get as much as half of their supply from wells. But no California agency has been tracking exactly how much is used or who uses it, even though nearly every other state regulates this resource.‚†Ä
The free-for-all has led to farmers in many areas pumping groundwater faster than the natural recharge. Water tables have rapidly dropped and, in some communities, homes have run out of water. During the 2012-to-2016 drought, about 3,500 domestic wells went dry."- Alastair Bland, CalMatters  We recently republished an extensive CalMatters story outlining the ins and outs of California's water development from the groundwater up. accessibility_caption: Photo by Daniel Sfeir in Broward County, Florida. Image may contain: 1 person, text
insta_description:
In these times of confusion, we have seen the craziest and selfish behaviors of our species. Stocking toilet paper or disinfecting stuff for a year or to be resold at a higher price on Amazon. 
It‚Äôs in times of crisis when we truly show what are we made of. There is no time for building up a new person magically, create new values or beliefs, people will react in their most primal, basic values for survival. 
The beauty is also that a considerable group of people will show traits and behave by caring for others, by been measured and just giving love. This group of people is hard wired to see the greater good as the other is for individuality. 
My invitation is to reflect on how you react in times of conflict and crisis, not only on these extreme scenarios but on smaller ones, on your challenges with your loved ones and at work. On those moments do you seek greater good or to save yourself and then the rest? Be honest. Yo don‚Äôt need to share the answer but to work on it to become better. 
It‚Äôs a time of reflection, to assume responsibility for the current state. It‚Äôs easy to say ‚Äúthis is out of my responsibility it‚Äôs a virus‚Äù but that‚Äôs not reality. We are all together in this one. 
What is clear is that something has to change. We need to start genuinely caring for others without boundaries or restrictions because of the consequence of not doing it is isolation. That‚Äôs our current state. 
We must end the era of the ‚ÄúI‚Äù and embrace the era of the ‚Äúwe‚Äù, the virus is the symptom not the desease. 
Happy day. üì∏: @maggiekirklandphoto .

.
My biggest struggle is saying no to temptation! üòí Hubby bought pizza dippers and.... WINGS üò´ I am not going to lie, I did have a few wings and dippers. TEMPTATION is going to be the thing I have to work on the most.
.

Our shipping facility is still shipping wine and taking extra precaution in the packing and handling of all wine. 
Take comfort in knowing that we are all in this together. Be kind to one another, have patience and stay positive. Take care of yourself and your loved ones. Let‚Äôs appreciate our surroundings and stay healthy together. We look forward to welcoming you back to our tasting room very soon and sharing our latest wines with you. #ellevateyourcellar

accessibility_caption: Photo by Lu Sea Lu in San Francisco, California. Image may contain: sky, bridge, outdoor and water
insta_description:
After spending 10 years forever cancelling holidays for work (life of a freelancer üôÑ), last year was the first year I decided enough was enough, life was too short. I was booking the trip and I was going on it. And I'm SO glad I did.

2019 continued to show us how short life really is and how you can never really know from one week to the next what will happen.

Was it completely over the top and irrational to get back from California and book tickets for @szigetofficial in Budapest as a surprise for my daughters 15th birthday? Absolutely. Do I regret it? Not one bit.

So many people said wait and do it next year for her 16th and my response was always "who knows what will have happened in a year, I'm doing it now whilst I can". And my god, that turned out to be the right decision.

Who knows if this year's trip will go ahead ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è and quite honestly it's the least of my concerns right now but yet again we are shown life is short and money comes and goes.

Book the trips when you can and soak up as much of the world as money and time allows you üåé

For now let's re live California 2019 shall we? üåÅ

insta_description: When I first started my journey visiting Joshua Tree was at the top of my list. Upon arriving in California I literally came to a fork in the road. Joshua Tree being one of them, and the Salton Sea being the other. Not really sure why I chose the Salton Sea. I think seeing water was on mind after driving across the country. After traveling 5 days without a shower I couldn‚Äôt tell you how good it felt to get naked and shower in the sun out in the desert haha. Incredible. Then I skipped Joshua tree and went to the coast. After finally visiting Joshua Tree...Im so thankful for being able to spend time there. I will FOR SURE be going back. I think one of the most incredible moments that I‚Äôve witnessed was driving south into the Cholla Cactus Garden during the Sun Set. In the distance it looked like a glowing ocean with energy. Something I will never forget. The Joshua Trees stand so still and peaceful, almost mesmerizing you while you stare at them. Nothing looks out of the ordinary in that place...it‚Äôs like everything belongs and you except it. It was like everything was strategically designed. Almost like each rock was specifically placed in each spot. I was even impressed with the roadways and how they flow through the different attractions. I still have a lot to learn about Joshua Tree so I will be coming back very soon‚úåüèº

accessibility_caption: Photo by ùí±ùíæùìãùíæùí∂ùìÉ ùí©ùíæùí∏ùëúùìÅùëí ùíØùëíùìàùìÅùëíùìá in Palm Springs, California with @revolve, @vicidolls, @arbonne, @prettylittlething, @palmspringsstyle, and @arbonnecanada. Image may contain: 1 person, selfie and closeup
insta_description:
One note does not make a symphony; one artist does not make an orchestra. üé∂‚ú®üé∂ Have our eyes awakened to a point in history where our decisions, steps, action, movement, have a grave effect on a singular person we have not met yet. Our decision to step in to our cars... drive to our destination, touch a railing or scratch our nose can fundamentally effect another persons reality in a nanosecond.  Whether it is in the immediate present or the never ending future. 
Collectively we have been called. Energetically and physically pulled to recognize how ONE SMALL STEP can effect the rest of humanity‚Äôs lives. Heavy ? Yes. Truth ... well, has it spoken loudly enough? 
Perhaps it wasn‚Äôt loud enough? 
Did we take it into consideration when it didn‚Äôt make a profound difference on our lives in the immediate? 
Did the word collective mean anything to us when it seemingly did ‚Äúnot matter?‚Äù What place does one persons power hold in this world ? 
We have heard this before ... all in theory of course. 
In a passing meme or a long winded speech. Did it hold power ? 
Possibly for a minute. Probably a few seconds... As the days pass I read message after message by citizens of this world pleading to its other counterpart ‚Äúto ... just ... stay ... home‚Äù. Whether we as mortals on this planet accept the fact that we have reached a point of no return... will the evidence be strong enough to hold water in the court of appreciation? The court of gratitude. The court of no judgement. The court of higher self. Will this be the truest catalyst of change? 
Have we listened to the meme? 
Have we acknowledged it‚Äôs worth? 
Have we surrendered to our higher self? 
Have we taken part in the collective? 
It‚Äôs Time...

insta_description:
Did you ever have a special place in nature to retreat and play as a kid? üçÉ Growing up, my family lived way out in the country. My brothers and I carved out our childhood in eucalyptus trees, irrigation gates and dirt roads. Every time we visited my Grandma, she had a massive pyracantha bush where my cousins, brothers and I would spend hours pretending it was our home. Those are memories that stay with you forever! ü•∞
‚Äî‚Äî
Seeing our boys use their imagination under these trees in Todos Santos made me smile, and reminded me of my Grandma‚Äôs yard. When I asked what they were doing, Harvey said matter-of-factly, ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre camping. Levi is my Dad and I‚Äôm his son, and the van is the store. Um, lady, can I buy some yogurts to take to our campsite?‚Äù Of course I obliged, charging two kisses for two yogurts. üòò They also pilfered my @electrolitmx for their little adventure! üòÖ
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
I hope these tiny moments last forever. That their imagination stays big and their dreams even bigger. As long as we‚Äôre fostering their sense of wonder, there will be countless adventures. And sometimes the best playground is the one you make within what nature provides! üåø
